english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Wave-Treading
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Someone once said: "When men of power and nobility build pavilions for leisure and enjoyment, there are those who still criticize them. How much more so when a Buddhist monk devotes himself to such things? Is this not mere ostentation and extravagance, a violation of the Way?"

    I replied: "It is not so. When people yearn to reach the Blue Lotus Buddha-realm or the White Jade Immortal-tower, it is for no other reason than that such places are pristine and unstained by dust. When a place is pure, the heart becomes so as well. There has never been a pure heart that fell prey to greed, wickedness, and torment. Viewed thus, even in this world of men, if one can but find a place of purity and cleanse one's thoughts through it, this too becomes the Buddha-realm, the Immortal-tower. Why then should we envy those distant abodes? Through such practice, one gradually treads the path of Buddha and Immortal alike.

    There is a certain Monk Hyuk, known as the Hermit of Three Peaks, a disciple of the Caodong lineage with refined sensibilities. He wandered long through the realm beyond the world, like a drifting cloud, until in a certain year of the Zhenyou era he chanced upon an ancient temple at Deoxing in Shouchun Prefecture. Finding the mountains and waters pleasing, he took up residence there. The tilted halls he set aright, the crumbling walls he rebuilt anew. He expanded the old grounds to provide ample space for the sangha to gather.

    Then he reflected: "When guests pass through, I must receive them with proper hospitality. Yet within these sacred halls, I cannot permit a place of mere sensual indulgence and revelry." So upon a plot of land beside the temple, where emerald waters formed a still pool rippling gently, he sank pilings and erected a pavilion above, roofing it with thatch. Seen from afar, it floats upon the waters like a light boat adorned with paintings upon the clear waves.

    When gatherings occur upon it, all the movements of seated guests—their bowing and straightening, their frowns and laughter—together with the shadows of cups and trays, chairs and tables, wine vessels and gaming boards, pour down upon the water's surface as if reflected in a clear mirror. In spring, when the waters run clear and luminous with sunlight, hundreds of fish swim in schools below, their forms visible and countable. In the cool months of autumn, when half the leaves have fallen and frost clarifies the water, red maples drape the banks and their images invert upon the waves, brilliant as silk washed in a great river.

    Such are the virtues of this water-pavilion, though there remain aspects too extraordinary to name in words. Those who see it know in their hearts—the eye perceives what the mouth cannot speak, and the painter's brush captures only its grosser outlines; pigment cannot render its truth.

    And so, by receiving guests in this place, who would dare say that a Buddhist monk should not enjoy such pavilions and vistas? From the imperial envoys to the wandering merchants crossing east and west, all who pass come to visit. As they linger in leisure and freedom, their spirits seem to mount blue cranes and white pheasants, soaring beyond the eight horizons. What need to speak of the White Jade Immortal-tower? And if even common visitors experience such transcendence, how much more so an old monk who sits in constant contemplation, saturated with this pure beauty? Surely he dwells already as neighbor to the Buddha-realm. How then does this violate the Way?

    Hyuk had always cherished letters and literature. Through my friend Han Hongbu, he asked me to write this record, hoping to adorn the pavilion and leave it to posterity. For two years I declined. Eventually Han's reproachful looks persuaded me, and I roughly set down these words, inscribing above the pavilion the name "Pavilion of Wave-Treading"—for the structure rises proud above the water.

    Alas, I too grow old. One day, when I lay down my official cap and withdraw from the world, clad in the turban of a recluse with staff in hand, I shall go to wander there, becoming the lord of wind and moon, pouring all the boundless beauty into one verse and one song to repay the longing I harbor in my heart today. If the spirits of lakes and mountains hear this wish, may they grant me time.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Blue Lotus Buddha-realm' and 'White Jade Immortal-tower' are metaphorical expressions for paradisiacal realms in Buddhist and Daoist cosmology.
    - Caodong (曹溪) lineage refers to the Chan (Zen) Buddhist school that traces back to the Sixth Patriarch.
    - '''Zhenyou era'' (貞祐) refers to a historical period during the Jin Dynasty.'
    - The name 'Pavilion of Wave-Treading' (凌波亭) is a poetic allusion suggesting lightness and grace, as if treading upon the water itself.
    - The closing image of the turban and staff represents the poet's desire to retire as a Daoist hermit in his old age.
